reviews.review_text: This is the best source. Enough has been said of this show-I was there, it was killer, but I've always thought the SBD was too sterile - this mix is sweet and captures the insanity better!!

This show is off-the-hook!! Check out the file, gd1982-04-19.89314.txt, to see the improvements made to this show.  This Matrix is the best-sounding source for this concert!  60% SBD and 40% AUD.  What a great mix!  Great job, Kevin Tobin!  You are the fucking shit!!

This show at the Baltimore Civic Center in Baltimore, MD is easily one of the best shows from 1982.  One of the future "Road Trips" releases should be this show, plus the previous two nights at the Hartford Civic Center in Hartford, CT.

I've been listening to this show all day at work and just downloaded it to my iTunes.  Now I just need to burn it for my car.  The 2nd set of this show ranks right up there with any Grateful Dead 2nd set of any show Ive ever heard!  I mean, just look at this fucking set, everybody!

The Raven Space is mind-altering.  You definitely should download this show.  The Wheel --> Truckin' --> Stella Blue --> Around And Around --> Good Lovin' --> Brokedown Palace are some of the best versions I've ever heard.  I sure haven't heard many Stella Blue's that can hold a candle to this one, people!!  And the Good Lovin kicks some serious ass!!

Check out my other reviews from awesome Grateful Dead shows!!

Danny from Northern Virginia outside of Washington, D.C.

PEACE-OUT!

ONE OF THE BEST OF '82 THIS SHOW IS GREAT FROM THE OPENING NOTES OF JACK STRAW.PEOPLE TALK ALOT ABOUT THE NIGHT BEFORE IN HARTFORD,AND YEAH THAT WAS GOOD BUT THIS NIGHT IN B-MORE WAS KILLER.BUT THE SHOW OF THAT TOUR IS HANDS DOWN 4/6/82 IN THE SPECTRUM,THIS ONE WAS A BIG PUDDLE NITE AS WAS 4/5/82.BUT THIS BEING AT THE VERY END OF THE TOUR THE BOY'S LIT UP BALTIMORE AGAIN.

What a show! I need a copy of this. Did not find this source on bt. maybe I missed it..in any case if you can help this guy please shoot me an email matt.eichen@gmail.com 

Def. a 5 star 82' performance.

Excellent Show Overall - Terrapin Has some Issues I'm not usually a huge fan of the 80's shows (especially later shows) but it was all before my time really, so that's not saying much. 

However, this really seems like a standout piece. From start to finish its packed with great tunes and little to no issue beyond Terrapin.

The sound for Terrapin seems to cut in and out like the boys have a piece of drywall being dropped in front of their mics every so often, which really sealed the deal on not adding this to my collection.

a smokin show my second, and by the end of this show I was hooked for good.
rockin Women R

Peggy-OMG!!! i can't believe no one has commented on this peggy-o.  it has all the crucial ingredients: jerry's voice is immaculate; his guitar phrasing is exquisite; and the solo is nice and long.  if you're a fan of peggy-o, i highly recommend you give this version a whirl.  you'll be happy you did.  and while you're here, don't be bashful about trying the cassidy and roses on for size.  listen to the crowd erupt in share joy after jerry's solo during cassidy.

Really about a 3 1/2 for me Good show but not spectacular. I find myself listening to 82 more and more however as there are some real treasures. 
I just love the electric On The Road Again which was the first set highlight for me. The second set run of FLAS>Franklin's>Estimated is excellent but the Terrapin falls a bit short. Nice Brokedown encore as well

Its ok, the Raven space is fun I was at this show and even then I thought it was only ok. The band played well enough. They're not exactly going through the motions but neither are they doing anything particularly interesting. There's just no real fire. For example in Franklin's Garcia's playing sounds choppy, as though he couldn't quite get his fingers to move fast enough and so sounds kinda behind the beat. He played this song at other times this year with much more fluidity and grace. This version is clumsy by comparison. The Raven Space is interesting for the novelty of the reading of The Raven by Baltimores most famous son Edgar Allen Poe but it's the only thing of any real uniqueness about this show. The rest is average and some like Franklin's Tower below average. File it under "pretty good but not worth keeping".

Amazing show. Amazing recording. Emotional Phil. Great recording, fantastic mix. What I remember from the show is Phil. As the show wound down, I drifted down from my nosebleed seat and ended up on the mezzanine, stage left (the Jerry side), standing amidst a group of very large but very mellow bikers. The band started "Brokedown Palace." Jerry sang, "Fare you well, my honey," and the crowd roared. And Phil, Phil just stopped playing and held out his arms as if trying to embrace everyone in the center. And as the concert ended, and the band left the stage, Phil stayed. He didn't want to go. He had had a great show, but it was over. He just stood alone onstage for a good minute, looking sad and forlorn and a little lost. Thanks for "The Raven," Phil, and thanks for taking all of us into your heart.
